content.problem:
Given data points $(t_1, y_1), \ldots, (t_m, y_m)$, find the best-fit line $y = c_0 + c_1 t$.

The system $c_0 + c_1 t_i = y_i$ for all $i$ can be written as:
\[
\underbrace{\begin{pmatrix} 1 & t_1 \\ 1 & t_2 \\ \vdots & \vdots \\ 1 & t_m \end{pmatrix}}_{A}
\underbrace{\begin{pmatrix} c_0 \\ c_1 \end{pmatrix}}_{x}
= \underbrace{\begin{pmatrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \\ \vdots \\ y_m \end{pmatrix}}_{b}
\]

For $m > 2$, this is typically overdetermined. Least squares minimizes the sum of squared vertical distances from data points to the line.
